

1. What is inheritance in Java? Why do we use inheritance?
-->Inheritance is an OOP feature in Java where one class acquires the properties and behaviors of another class using the extends keyword.
  The existing class is called the parent/superclass
  The new class is called the child/subclass
  
  Why do we use inheritance?
    Code reusability
    Method overriding
    Reduces code duplication
    Supports runtime polymorphism
    Creates IS-A relationship




2.Explain the concept of parent (super) class and child (sub) class in Java. How does inheritance establish a relationship between them?
-->Parent/Superclass → Class whose properties are inherited.
    Child/Subclass → Class that inherits properties from parent.
    
    Inheritance creates an IS-A relationship.
    
    Example:
    
    class Vehicle {
        void start() {
            System.out.println("Vehicle starts");
        }
    }
    
    class Car extends Vehicle {
        void drive() {
            System.out.println("Car drives");
        }
    }
    
    Here:
    
    Vehicle → Parent class
    Car → Child class
    Car IS-A Vehicle




3.What is single inheritance in Java? Explain with an example.
-->When one child class inherits from one parent class.
  Example
  class A {
      void display() {
          System.out.println("Class A");
      }
  }
  
  class B extends A {
      void show() {
          System.out.println("Class B");
      }
  }
  B inherits from A.



4.What is multilevel inheritance in Java? Explain with an example.
-->When a class inherits from another inherited class.
    Example
    class A {
        void methodA() {
            System.out.println("A");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        void methodB() {
            System.out.println("B");
        }
    }
    
    class C extends B {
        void methodC() {
            System.out.println("C");
        }
    }
    Here:  
      C inherits B
      B inherits A



5.Why is multiple inheritance not supported in Java?
-->Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity problems (Diamond Problem).
    Example Problem
    class A {
        void show() {}
    }
    
    class B {
        void show() {}
    }
    
    // class C extends A, B  // Not allowed
    
    Java cannot decide which show() method to inherit.
    
    Java achieves multiple inheritance using interfaces.




6.What is hierarchical inheritance in Java? Provide an example.
-->When multiple child classes inherit from one parent class.
    Example
    class Animal {
        void eat() {
            System.out.println("Eating");
        }
    }
    
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void bark() {
            System.out.println("Barking");
        }
    }
    
    class Cat extends Animal {
        void meow() {
            System.out.println("Meowing");
        }
    }
    Both Dog and Cat inherit Animal.



7.What is hybrid inheritance in Java? Explain with an example.
-->Hybrid inheritance is a combination of more than one type of inheritance. 
    Java does not support hybrid inheritance with classes directly, but it can be achieved using interfaces.
    
    Example
    interface A {
        void show();
    }
    
    class B {
        void display() {
            System.out.println("Display");
        }
    }
    
    class C extends B implements A {
        public void show() {
            System.out.println("Show");
        }
    }




