9.How does constructor chaining work in inheritance?
-->Constructor chaining means calling parent constructor from child constructor using super().
    Example
    class A {
        A() {
            System.out.println("Parent Constructor");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        B() {
            super();
            System.out.println("Child Constructor");
        }
    }
      Output:
        Parent Constructor
        Child Constructo
    


10.Can a subclass access private members of the superclass?
-->No, private members cannot be accessed directly outside the class.
    
    But they can be accessed indirectly using:
    
    Public methods
    Protected getters/setters
    Example
    class A {
        private int x = 10;
    
        public int getX() {
            return x;
        }
    }



11.Can we override static methods? Why or why not?
-->No, static methods cannot be overridden because they belong to the class, not objects.
    
    They are only method hidden.
    
    Example
    class A {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("A");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("B");
        }
    }




12.What is HAS-A relationship and IS-A relationship in OOP?
-->In Java, IS-A and HAS-A are the two primary ways classes relate to one another to achieve code reusability and modularity
    1. IS-A Relationship (Inheritance):
          An IS-A relationship is based on inheritance. It represents a specialized version of a general class where a "child" class
          inherits all the properties and behaviors of a "parent" class
          
          Implementation: Achieved using the extends keyword (for classes) or the implements keyword (for interfaces).
          
          Key Characteristic: It is unidirectional; for example, a Dog "is-an" Animal, but an Animal is not necessarily a Dog.
          Example:
              class Animal { }
              class Dog extends Animal { } // Dog IS-A Animal
              
            Purpose: Primarily used for polymorphism and to avoid code redundancy by inheriting fields and methods.
    
    2. HAS-A Relationship (Composition/Aggregation)
    
          A HAS-A relationship is based on association. It occurs when one class contains a reference to an instance of another 
          class as a member field.
          
          Implementation: Achieved by declaring an object of one class as an instance variable in another class.
    
    Two Forms:
        Composition: A strong relationship where the contained object cannot exist without the parent (e.g., a Car has an Engine).
        
        Aggregation: A weak relationship where both objects can exist independently (e.g., a Library has Books).
        
        class Engine { }
        class Car {
            private Engine engine = new Engine(); // Car HAS-A Engine
        }
        
        Purpose: Promotes loose coupling and flexibility, as the implementation of the contained object can be changed without affecting
        the parent class.
        






13.What happens when a method is declared final in a superclass?
-->A final method cannot be overridden by subclasses.
    Example
    class A {
        final void display() {
            System.out.println("Final Method");
        }
    }



14.Can we override a private method? Why?
-->No.
  Because private methods are not visible to subclasses, so they are not inherited.



